{{Infobox saint | name = Abibos of Nekresi | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | titles = Saint | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = [[Mtskheta]], Georgia | venerated_in = Orthodox Church | beatified_date = | beatified_place = | beatified_by = | canonized_date = | canonized_place = | canonized_by = | major_shrine = | feast_day = November 29 | attributes = | patronage = | issues = | suppressed_date = | suppressed_by = }}
'''Abibus of Nekressi''' ({{lang-ka|აბიბოს ნეკრესელი|tr}}) (fl. 6th century) was one of the [[Thirteen Assyrian Fathers|thirteen Assyrian apostles]] of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and the [[bishop]] of [[Nekresi]] who arrived in Georgia under the leadership of [[Thirteen Assyrian Fathers|St. Ioane of Zedazeni]] (John of Zedazeni). He began his activity as bishop in a village which was located in the hills in the eastern region of [[Kakheti]]. According to the chronicle Life of Kartli, he was spreading Christianity not only among Georgians but also among the mountain tribes such as the Dagestani/Didoians, the ancient predecessors of modern [[Dagestan]].<ref name="pravo">[http://www.pravoslavie.ru/7366.html/ Holy Martyr Abibos of Nekresi (6th Century)] Retrieved on 21 Feb 2018</ref>
At that time there was a dark period of [[Sasanian Empire|Persian rule]] in eastern Georgia. The main religion of Persians was [[Zoroastrianism]] - worship of fire. St. Abibos is said to have doused a sacred Zoroastrian flame with water. He was captured by the pagan priests, was tied up and beaten before be brought to the [[marzban]]. [[Simeon the Stylite]] of the Wonderful Mountain sent him a letter, an [[eulogia]] (probably a piece of prosphoron) and a staff to strengthen his soul. He was stoned to death by [[Zoroastrian]] [[Persian people|Persians]] at [[Rekhi]] and his body was dragged from the city and cast to the beasts.<ref name="pravo"/>
In spite of the stringent prohibition to take his body the priests and monks of Rekhi stole it. They buried it with great honor at [[Samtavisi Cathedral|Samtavisi Monastery]] (located midway between [[Mtskheta]] and [[Gori, Georgia|Gori]]). During the rule of [[Stephen III of Iberia|Prince Stepanoz]] of [[Kartli]], the relics of St. Abibos were relocated from [[Samtavisi Cathedral|Samtavisi]] to [[Samtavro Monastery]] in Mtskheta. They were buried under the holy altar at [[Samtavro Monastery|Samtavro Church]].<ref>[http://travelgeorgia.ru/325/ About Sights – Nekresi Monastery] Retrieved on 21 Feb 2018</ref>
His [[feast day]] had been kept on November 12 through 1700, but later changed to December 12 on the Gregorian calendar and November 29 on the Julian calendar correspondingly.
